---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import BlogHero from '../../components/BlogHero.astro';
import BlogFigure from '../../components/BlogFigure.astro';
import RelatedPosts from '../../components/RelatedPosts.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug, postsBySlugs, RELATED_POSTS } from '../../data/posts';

const post = postBySlug('kitchen-refit-belfast-sink-granite-ayrshire')!;
const relatedPosts = postsBySlugs(RELATED_POSTS[post.slug] ?? []).slice(0, 3);
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${BASE}/gallery/ayrshire-kitchen-refit-belfast-sink-granite-15-1600w.jpg`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: { '@type': 'Person', name: post.author, worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` } },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  keywords: [post.keyword],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  ogType="article"
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        A kitchen put back in Ayrshire after underfloor damp works. The room
        had to come apart before the damp could be fixed. Once the floor was
        sound again, the refit put everything back in its place — electrics,
        Belfast sink and tap, granite worktops, cabinets and the original
        tiles.
      </p>
    </header>

    <BlogHero slug="ayrshire-kitchen-refit-belfast-sink-granite-15" />

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg cv-auto">
      <h2>What the job involved</h2>
      <p>
        Electrics went back on first — sockets, switches and the under-cabinet
        lighting tested before anything covered them. The Belfast sink was
        reset on its carcass with a fresh bed, the tap plumbed in, and the
        granite worktops offered up, drilled and lowered into place.
      </p>
      <p>
        Cabinets were refitted, doors hung and adjusted to a tight line, and
        the original splashback tiles put back where they came from. Sealing,
        silicone and a final clean finished the day.
      </p>

      <BlogFigure slug="ayrshire-kitchen-refit-belfast-sink-granite-15" />

      <h2>Things to think about before you start</h2>
      <p>
        Granite is heavy. If worktops are coming out and going back, the floor
        and carcasses underneath have to be dead true before anything sits on
        top — a millimetre of bounce in the base cabinet turns into a
        hairline crack in the stone over time. Any damp or floor work is the
        right time to reset levels.
      </p>
      <p>
        Keep the old tiles if you can. Matching a discontinued splashback is
        often impossible, and replacing the whole wall for the sake of three
        cut tiles at the sink is a lot more cost and dust than most people
        want. Lift carefully, label the backs, and store them flat.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you are in Ayrshire and need something similar, Fraser will come
        and look for free. Call <strong>07900 255876</strong> or WhatsApp
        <strong>+44 7472 223323</strong>. FREE no-obligation quote, every job
        priced individually.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  {relatedPosts.length > 0 && (
    <RelatedPosts posts={relatedPosts} eyebrow="Keep reading" heading="Related posts" variant="tinted" />
  )}

  <CTABlock
    heading="Kitchen coming apart for damp works?"
    sub="We can put it back when the floor is ready — give Fraser a call."
    location="Ayrshire"
  />
</BaseLayout>
